  "description": "Identification on iNaturalist is a consensus system with rules. It is robust for common, well-documented taxa and fragile for rare or cryptic ones.\n¶Mechanics IDs are weighted by taxonomic alignment and agreement. Community ID can override a single expert if not supported by evidence. IDs can be withdrawn or replaced, but downstream data may already be synced. Early IDs can anchor subsequent identifications, especially when CV suggestions or popular taxa are involved. ¶Evidence thresholds by taxon (general pattern) Conspicuous species: often identifiable with minimal evidence but still prone to look-alikes. Cryptic complexes: may require microscopic or genetic evidence; iNaturalist cannot capture this directly. Juveniles: many taxa are unidentifiable to species at early life stages. When evidence cannot support a species-level ID, the responsible choice is to stop at the lowest confident rank.\n",
  "name": "How identification works",
